://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-introductory-tutorial/">Bodysuit with Corset Cups <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="24"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-measurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong>Dressmaker’s Treasury will equip you with a range of necessary tools and techniques which every professional must possess for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>It will help you get more confident. You will know how to: </strong></p><ul><li>Choose the right strategy for making a garment after your first meeting with the client;</li><li>Take necessary measurements correctly and prepare and fill out an order form;</li><li>Choose the right basic pattern and adjust it after your client’s measurements with the help of automatic pattern adjustments calculation tables;</li><li>Avoid common mistakes which result in ill-fitting necklines by choosing the right sewing technique.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;5h 16m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-27-making-a-basic-corset-pattern/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-27-making-a-basic-corset-pattern/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2017-12-02T13:19:27+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2017-12-02T13:19:27+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2017"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 27. Making a Basic Corset Pattern."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 27. Making a Basic Corset Pattern."><meta itemprop="description" content="under-bust darts in corsets and explain why it is so important to choose the right kind of a basic pattern for further work"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding and Evening Dresses. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding and evening dresses. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 27. Making a Basic Corset Pattern.</h1><p><strong>It is time for a little bit of theory.</strong></p><p>I want to talk about under-bust darts in corsets and explain why it is so important to choose the right kind of a basic pattern for further work.</p><p>The thing is that my standard corset patterns include under-bust darts of different widths to ensure a good fit along the neckline depending on its type: strapless, boat-neck, or low V-neck. Therefore, you will inevitably get an ill-fitting garment if you choose the wrong pattern from the start.</p><p>I would like to tell you in more detail about the construction of these standard patterns to highlight the importance of choosing the right one for your garment.</p><p><strong>So how were these standard corset patterns made? </strong></p><p><strong>I have made a very rough sketch of a corset cup pattern on the writing board. </strong>We will talk about three-part cups in more detail in a separate section of “Dressmaker’s Treasury” dedicated to see-through corsets with sew-in multi-part cups. But even in this book I must still touch upon the question of sew-in multi-part cups to explain you about bust princess seam in corsets cut one piece with cups.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2027.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>You can see a schematic drawing of a three-part corset cup in the top right corner of the board. </strong>There are special calculation methods for constructing such cups: you draw a grid, calculate all parameters, and draft a base. Then you work on the shape: transfer darts, make princess seams, etc. I will not delve into the details of it in this book but I must definitely illustrate certain key aspects.</p><p><strong>I am not trying to urge you to make your own corset cup patterns. On the contrary, I will be very happy if you use my standard patterns as much as you like! But I do want you to understand how they were made and in what way they differ from each other so you can fully understand the importance of choosing the right pattern for each new garment!&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong></p><p><strong>The classic base of a sew-in corset cup consists of three parts: </strong></p><p>1 - Top piece,</p><p>2 - Bottom front piece, and</p><p>3 - Bottom side piece.</p><p>The bottom front piece attaches to a centre bridge piece while the bottom side piece attaches to a side bridge piece cut as part of the back.</p><p><strong>Here is the first important moment: </strong>in my standard pattern of a multi-part corset cup, the bust point is already shifted to the side as compared to the actual bust apex point (because we measure Bust Princess Seam to Bust Princess Seam instead of Bust Apex to Bust Apex). The amount of shift depends on the bust circumference, as well as on size groups into which cups are classified according to the existing standards. For the smallest sizes, for example, the bust point is shifted to the side by about 3mm.</p><p><strong>Thus a shift of the bust point is already accounted for in my standard cup pattern. </strong></p><p><strong>There are also special methods for calculating widths of under-bust dart (between pieces 2 and 3), centre front dart (between pieces 1 and 2), and side dart (between pieces 1 and 3).</strong></p><p><strong>It is necessary to precisely measure distances between certain points of the bust before you can start calculating dart opening widths for a corset cup like this.</strong></p><p>Only experienced professionals who have a natural feel for it can take these measurements precisely.</p><p><strong>You can see the reference points on the drawing I made. </strong></p><p><strong>Point (1) - lateral point.</strong> Marked on young women, bra off, arm raised. It lies at the border between the mammary gland and the underarm.</p><p><strong>Point (2) - medial point.</strong> It is the point where the mammary glands come together.</p><p><strong>Point (3) - bottom point.</strong> The breast must normally be lifted up in order to find this point.</p><p><strong>Point (4) - root point.</strong> It is found in the upper part of the breast where the mammary gland slant begins. If the woman is wearing a bra, this point is normally positioned 1.5 or 2cm toward the centre from the bottom of the shoulder strap. Bra shoulder straps are constructed with respect to this point.</p><p><strong>Point (5) - bust apex point.</strong> This is the most prominent point of the mammary gland.</p><p><strong>These five key points are responsible for the anatomy of the mammary gland and necessary for constructing a basic cup pattern. </strong></p><p><strong>How to calculate the width of the under-bust dart? </strong></p><p><strong>You must, first of all, measure your cup’s width. </strong>Cup Width is basically the length of the horizontal arc going from the lateral point (1) to the medial point (2) through the bust apex point (5) minus 3-6cm depending on the breast size group.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2027.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Then, you find the projection of this horizontal arc onto the body. </strong>It is section A-B measured between vertical lines going perpendicular to the waistline through the lateral point (1) and the medial point (2).</p><p><strong>Under-Bust Dart Width is calculated as difference between the Cup Width and the length of the projected horizontal arc: </strong></p><p><strong>UBDW = "Cup Width" – section A-B</strong></p><p><strong>Under-Bust Dart Width is distributed equally to either side of the vertical axis. </strong></p><p><strong>Front Dart Width and Side Dart Width are the same and calculated as difference between the length of the vertical bust arc and the length of its projection. </strong></p><p>Up to 1cm may be added to this value during more precise calculations depending on the breast size group.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2027.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The vertical arc goes between the bust bottom point (3) and the root point (4) through the bust apex point (5). </strong></p><p><strong>Its projection is section C-D </strong>going between perpendicular lines drawn through points (3) and (4).</p><p><strong>Therefore, </strong></p><p><strong>FDW = SDW = Vertical Arc – section C-D</strong></p><p><strong>You need to use special-purpose rulers to measure the horizontal bust arc and the vertical bust arc correctly. The client will also need to take off her bra. </strong></p><p>Her torso must be bare! And she must naturally be young enough and have firm enough breasts for you to take these measurements precisely. Unfortunately, it becomes impossible to construct a perfect cup pattern like this starting from a certain age.</p><p><strong>It is quite hard to construct your own cup pattern considering all these limitations! </strong></p><p><strong>The front dart opening is distributed in equal halves from either side of the horizontal axis. </strong></p><p><strong>Side Dart Width is distributed the following way: 0.6 of it falls upon the top and the remaining 0.4 falls upon the bottom. </strong></p><p><strong>In addition, I must also point out a very important spot on my basic multi-part cup draft. </strong>There are two areas in the bottom part of the pattern where the cup overlaps with the bridge. As the result, the Under-Bust Dart Width will be slightly reduced.</p><p>I have explained this part of the theory to give you a proper understanding of how you calculate dart widths and distribute them against perpendicular axes.</p><p><strong>Another important aspect of our calculations lies in the fact that you can only make a pattern of a non-see-through corset when you have a pattern of a sew-in cup which can be used for constructing integrated cups, i.e. cups cut one piece with the corset. </strong></p><p><strong>Now that we have constructed the base of our sew-in multi-part cup, we can start working on a basic pattern of a corset cut one piece with cups. </strong></p><p><strong>I draw a vertical princess seam which divides in half the top part of the cup. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2027.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>The shaded part of the piece is supposed to fall upon the centre front piece (1) of the corset with integrated cups. </strong></p><p>And this means I need to position it so as to make section A-B parallel to the centre front line (A1-B1).</p><p><strong>I position the shaded piece correspondingly. </strong></p><p><strong>This results in a dart between the two halves of the top cup piece, and the central front dart does not close properly. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2027.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p><p>The top edge of the left part of the top cup piece has the same shape as the boat-neck edge of the centre front piece of the corset.</p><p><strong>The right (non-shaded) part of the top cup piece is supposed to join with the side front piece (2) of our corset with integrated cups. </strong></p><p><strong>I position it correspondingly, which results in the closing of the side dart. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2027.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Please note the uneven distribution of the top dart on the multi-part cup as compared to the princess seam:</strong> the part of its opening facing the centre piece is smaller than the part facing the side piece. The side dart may also be partially preserved depending on the side seam length.</p><p><strong>This explains why the front princess seams of a corset with integrated cups have different inclines at the top:</strong> the princess seam on the centre front piece is closer to a vertical line while the one on the side front piece has a more distinct incline.</p><p><strong>I receive very many E-mails asking about that difference in the inclines of princess seams on the centre front piece and the side front piece of non-see-through corsets.</strong> Now you know that it arises because of certain construction peculiarities.</p><p><strong>We have only been talking about the top part of the cup until now. </strong></p><p><strong>Now let us talk about the bottom part and the under-bust dart. </strong></p><p><strong>The bottom parts of our multi-part cup overlap with the bridge.</strong> The bridge is positioned under the bust and clings to the body very tightly and the cup pieces basically emerge from under it at a straight angle.</p><p><strong>You need to divide the bottom cup pieces and the bridge pieces along the princess seam lines and make these princess seam lines smooth to build a pattern of a corset cut one piece with cups. </strong>It is the only way to achieve a smooth shape of the princess seam in the under-bust area of the side front corset piece. In other words, it is the only way to create a smooth transition from the cup to the corset.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2027.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>But we know that the corset tends to stay a little loose in the under-bust area.</strong> I mentioned it many times and you already know that it is impossible to achieve a tight fit under the bust in non-see-through corsets with two front princess seams.</p><p><strong>This is why such corsets made of three front pieces are better-suited for women with full breasts. </strong>It is explained in great detail in all “Plus-Size” courses offered at the Corset Academy. Women with full breasts feel comfortable in such corsets with a little space in the under-bust area: the breasts sink down just a little filling in the hollows and, as the result, less of the bust is pushed out at the top, the woman feels more comfortable and her full bust does not look vulgar. I always recommend corset patterns with two front princess seams for full-breasted women.</p><p><strong>What will happen if we change the configuration of the princess seam in the under-bust area to adjust the corset pattern to client’s measurements and make it cling to the body under the bust? </strong></p><p><strong>Imagine a situation like this:</strong> we are experienced patter-makers who can take all anthropological bust measurements with great accuracy and construct perfect multi-part cups. We have prepared a basic pattern of a corset with integrated cups for our client. But its measurements don’t coincide with client’s measurements along the under-bust line. In other words, the aggregate length of the under-bust line on the centre front piece and the side front piece exceeds our client’s Under-Bust Width Front.</p><p><strong>And this happens because </strong>the depth and width of the under-bust darts were originally calculated for sew-in multi-part cups. They were not calculated for cups cut one piece with the corset! And these are two absolutely different constructions!</p><p><strong>The first idea which strikes any beginner </strong>not acquainted with the theory of constructing cup patterns is to take in the princess seams starting from the under-bust line. For example, take in 5mm and re-draw the princess seam lines in the area between the bust line and the waistline.</p><p><strong>But a change like this will produce an absolutely terrible effect!</strong></p><p><strong>The corset itself will indeed cling to the body but the cups will start gapping at the top! </strong></p><p><strong>And that is when you get real problems with the neckline fit! </strong></p><p>These notorious problems seem to have been arising more and more often judging from your E-mails. Haven’t I warned you against changing the front princess seams? Please do not neglect this warning!</p><p><strong>Take a look at pictures of garments made after my standard patterns of non-see-through corsets by subscribers who did change the shape of bust princess seams and took them in. Have you ever wondered why there is so much décor along the neckline? It is all because the cups are gapping at the top and they had to disguise this somehow! </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2027.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>What to do when you need to adjust the corset after client’s measurements though? </strong>Right now we are talking about corsets with two bust princess seams at the front.</p><p><strong>But there are corsets with four front princess seams, i.e. with a front made of five pieces. </strong>These additional intermediate princess seams are there for a reason: they allow you to make necessary adjustments to match your client’s Under-Bust Width Front measurement.</p><p><strong>If you still want to use a pattern with just two front princess seams, </strong>then make additional notches on the side pieces and remove excess fabric by making darts in relevant areas.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2027.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>This will help you preserve garment balance! </strong></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20boat.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/